  "prompt": "Why did Apple change its name from Apple Computers Incorporated to Apple Inc?\"?",
  "response": "Apple officially changed its name from \"Apple Computer, Inc.\" to \"Apple Inc.\" on January 9, 2007, to reflect the company's expansion beyond just computers. At the time, Apple was increasingly diversifying its product lineup, moving into areas like consumer electronics, software, and digital services.\n\nThe announcement of the name change coincided with the launch of the **iPhone**, a groundbreaking product that marked Apple's entry into the mobile phone market and signaled its transformation into a broader technology company. Steve Jobs, Apple's then-CEO, explained that the name change was necessary because Apple was no longer just a computer company. It was now a company focused on innovation across multiple markets, including music (iPod, iTunes), mobile (iPhone), and eventually other areas like wearables (Apple Watch) and services (App Store, iCloud, Apple Music).\n\nThis rebranding underscored Apple's shift from being a niche computer manufacturer to a global leader in consumer technology and innovation.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
